<div class="comment"><div class="commtext c00">Unfortunately, GPU&#x27;s are old news now. When it comes to perf&#x2F;watt&#x2F;dollar, TPU&#x27;s are substantially ahead for both training and inference. There&#x27;s a sparsity disadvantage with the trailing-edge TPU devices such as v4 but if you care about large-scale training of any sort, it&#x27;s not even close. Additionally, Tenstorrent p300 devices are hitting the market soon enough, and there&#x27;s lots of promising stuff is coming on Xilinx side of the AMD shop: the recent Versal chips allow for AI compute-in-network capabilities that puts NVIDIA Bluefield&#x27;s supposed programmability to shame. NVIDIA likes to say Bluefield is like a next-generation SmartNIC, but compared to actually field-programmable Versal stuff, it&#x27;s more like 100BASE-T cards from the 90s.<p>I think it&#x27;s very naive to assume that GPU&#x27;s will continue to dominate the AI landscape.</div><div class="reply"><p><font size="1"><u><a href="reply?id=44368272&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D44365320%2344368272" rel="nofollow">reply</a></u></font></div></div></td></tr>
